{
  "id": "1.4",
  "title": "First-Order Logic Notation",
  "order": 4,
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "In first-order logic (FOL), we translate English sentences into precise symbolic notation. This allows us to analyze arguments with mathematical rigor and avoid the ambiguity of natural language."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The basic building blocks of FOL are **predicates**, **constants**, **variables**, **connectives**, and **quantifiers**. Let's learn each one."
    },
    {
      "type": "symbols",
      "title": "Predicates & Constants",
      "symbols": [
        {
          "symbol": "Happy(x)",
          "name": "Predicate",
          "meaning": "A property applied to something",
          "example": "Happy(alice) = 'Alice is happy'"
        },
        {
          "symbol": "alice",
          "name": "Constant",
          "meaning": "A name for a specific individual",
          "example": "socrates, bob, earth"
        },
        {
          "symbol": "x, y, z",
          "name": "Variable",
          "meaning": "A placeholder for any individual",
          "example": "Used with quantifiers"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "symbols",
      "title": "Logical Connectives",
      "symbols": [
        {
          "symbol": "∧",
          "name": "Conjunction",
          "meaning": "AND - both must be true",
          "example": "A ∧ B = 'A and B'"
        },
        {
          "symbol": "∨",
          "name": "Disjunction",
          "meaning": "OR - at least one is true",
          "example": "A ∨ B = 'A or B'"
        },
        {
          "symbol": "→",
          "name": "Implication",
          "meaning": "IF...THEN",
          "example": "A → B = 'If A then B'"
        },
        {
          "symbol": "¬",
          "name": "Negation",
          "meaning": "NOT - opposite is true",
          "example": "¬A = 'not A'"
        },
        {
          "symbol": "↔",
          "name": "Biconditional",
          "meaning": "IF AND ONLY IF",
          "example": "A ↔ B = 'A iff B'"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "symbols",
      "title": "Quantifiers",
      "symbols": [
        {
          "symbol": "∀x",
          "name": "Universal",
          "meaning": "FOR ALL x",
          "example": "∀x.Human(x) → Mortal(x)"
        },
        {
          "symbol": "∃x",
          "name": "Existential",
          "meaning": "THERE EXISTS an x",
          "example": "∃x.Dog(x) ∧ Happy(x)"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "title": "Translation Examples",
      "premises": [
        "Alice is happy → Happy(alice)",
        "All dogs bark → ∀x.Dog(x) → Barks(x)",
        "Some cats are lazy → ∃x.Cat(x) ∧ Lazy(x)"
      ],
      "conclusion": "Notice how 'all' uses → but 'some' uses ∧",
      "note": "This difference is crucial and will be explained in the Syllogistic Logic module."
    },
    {
      "type": "quiz",
      "question": "How would you translate 'Bob runs' into first-order logic?",
      "options": [
        "bob(Runs)",
        "Runs(bob)",
        "∀x.Runs(x)",
        "bob ∧ Runs"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "explanation": "The predicate 'Runs' is applied to the constant 'bob'. Predicates are capitalized, constants are lowercase, and the constant goes inside the parentheses."
    }
  ],
  "key_symbols": ["∀", "∃", "→", "∧", "∨", "¬", "↔"]
}
